704479f-c.title: Brooklyn: Fulton Street - Hicks Street
704479f-c.text:
47 Fulton Street, north side, at the head of Hicks
Street, showing the old Long Island Bank, established in
1824. The bank occupied this building fromm 1876 to 1880.
In 1892 the bank was at 186 Remsen Strret. A broom sell-
ing concern later took over the builditg. Two signs at
the entrance to the building read: ''Spriral Tube Brushes''
and ''Rattan-Bass Push Brooms.''
1923
Views 1,2
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection
MAY BE REPRODUCED
(3)
Another view of the old bank building.
February 5, 1931
P. L. Sperr
NO REPRODUCTIDNS

704905f-a.title: Brooklyn: Hicks Street - Fulton Street
704905f-a.text:
Hicks Street, east side, south of Fulton Street, to and including
Poplar Street. The buildings in the background, south of Poplar Street
have since 1905 been demolished and P.S. No. 2 is on the site. The
second building from the foreground, made of frame, has been replaced
by a one story brick building. Note the gathering making ready for a
picnic trip.
About 1905.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
MAY BE REPRODUCED.

704904f-a.title: Brooklyn: Hicks Street - Fulton Street
704904f-a.text:
Hicks Street, west side, at Fulton Street. Also shown is 43-51
Fulton Street, north side, at the foot of Hicks Street. Te Lenox House
is at No. 43. The Fulton Street Elevated Lines of the B.M.T. are in the
foreground.
February 5, 1931.
P. L. Sperr.
